# Evidence-command DENY baseline (ADR-022). One bare program name per line.
#
# TEMPLATE-OWNED, not consumer policy: unlike .truth/evidence-allow (which
# you own and copier never clobbers), this file is maintained by the
# truth-ledger template and a `copier update` keeps it current. Do not
# edit it -- your changes will be overwritten. You control what RUNS via
# the allowlist; this file only removes footguns from that choice.
#
# What this is: an anti-footgun guardrail. The allowlist is the security
# boundary (ADR-021) -- only bare allowlisted names run, and this is NOT a
# claim to enumerate every dangerous program (that blocklist trap is
# ADR-021's lesson). It lists ONLY programs whose sole job is to run OTHER
# programs -- shells and generic executors -- which are never a read-only
# evidence check. If one of these is on your allowlist by accident, the
# evidence screen refuses it anyway (deny-wins), because allowlisting a
# shell silently turns the read-only screen into arbitrary execution.
#
# What this is NOT: it does not touch the ACCEPTANCE screen (ADR-014
# oracles execute repository code on purpose -- `bash run-tests.sh` is
# legitimate there). And it does not hard-deny grey-zone interpreters/VCS
# with plausible read-only uses (git, python, awk, sed, curl, ...); for
# those `truth doctor` warns instead, leaving the policy to you.
#
# To run repository code on purpose, use an acceptance oracle (ADR-014),
# not an evidence command.

# shells -- run arbitrary commands from a string or script
sh
bash
zsh
dash
ksh
csh
tcsh
fish
ash
busybox

# generic executors -- their sole purpose is to launch another program,
# which then runs as an ARGUMENT the screen does not program-check. This
# list covers the well-known ones; it is NOT a completeness claim (that
# trap is ADR-021's lesson) -- the allowlist stays the boundary. `time` is
# the classic footgun: innocent-looking ("time my grep") but `time <cmd>`
# runs <cmd>, and it is both a /usr/bin/time binary and a shell keyword.
env
xargs
nice
nohup
timeout
setsid
stdbuf
watch
command
time
flock
ionice
taskset
unshare
nsenter
chroot
runuser
prlimit
chrt
eatmydata
script
expect
socat
parallel

# privilege escalation that runs a command
sudo
doas
su
